<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="d7e3b7e42b558d4fb4d2cfdeea895426" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Starter-lingly good Nazgûl!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17227'>Alex "El Spanko" McElhinney</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=17227&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 20, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Starter-lingly good Nazgûl!<br />
Here at last is the long awaited (?) sequel to my article Uncommonly good Nazgûl. Once again I will attempt to analyse the new batch of Ringwraiths from the Shadows and Black rider sets, and as before I aim this article at newcomers to the game- therefore I will avoid talk of rare cards at all costs.<br />
<br />
I’ve noticed a few articles about prophesising the end or downfall of LOTR CCG, and having seen it happen with so many other games I’m determined not to let this one go.<br />
Now the films are over and off the cinema screens can the game survive? Will multitudes of new cards really keep things going? Not likely. <br />
<br />
What will prevent a game from disappearing is the influx of players. Young or old, a new player must be introduced to any game in a sensible manner; this really goes out to Tournament Directors and Product Champions, though any one who enjoys the game will take heed.<br />
<br />
Demo decks! Have them on you, and make them as close to starters as possible. Rare free is preferable. Be prepared to give away piles of commons and uncommons, we’ve all got loads kicking around. I’m not talking dumping here- put together ‘packages’, it takes no time at all.<br />
<br />
Having said that, on with the article proper. This is aimed at beginners, to guide and inspire, (veteran players may also use the article as a lesson to hand out to their Padawan learners) please rate and review accordingly.<br />
<br />
There’s never been a better time to get involved with The Lord of the Rings ccg, especially as what are in my mind Tolkien’s most compelling creations- the Ringwraiths- are more accessible than ever before.<br />
<br />
Danger! Fart Salt!<br />
The Gandalf starter from Shadows should really have been called the Nazgûl starter; the title Gandalf starter is misleading. The Nazgûl cards in the box are…<br />
<br />
Úlairë Cantëa, Fourth of the Nine Riders<br />
TW cost: 5 Str: 10 Vit: 3 Site: 3<br />
While Úlairë Cantëa is at a forest or dwelling site, he is strength +2 and fierce.<br />
(11S220)<br />
<br />
Forests and dwellings are a Nazgûl’s best friend and I shall look at the site path in more detail later. Suffice to say that there is no reason for Cantëa not to be Str 12 and fierce, like his brother Toldëa, only for 1 less twilight!<br />
<br />
Úlairë Lemenya, Fifth of the Nine Riders<br />
TW cost: 4 Str: 9 Vit: 2 Site: 3<br />
Each character skirmishing Úlairë Lemenya who has resistance 5 or less is strength –3.<br />
(11S221)<br />
<br />
Ok, so burdens now reduce everyone’s resistance (which defaults to 6 if not printed on the card remember), and that helps Lemenya a little. –3 strength isn’t really a great deal given the amount of pumps and weapons out there, and of course your opponent’s not likely to give you satisfaction by assigning him to someone you can beat easily. Why is it Mr. Lemenya fairs so badly when being given special abilities?<br />
<br />
<br />
Úlairë Nelya, Third of the Nine Riders <br />
TW cost: 5 Str: 10 Vit: 3 Site: 2<br />
Fierce. Shadow: Exert Úlairë Nelya to replace the fellowship’s current site with a site from your adventure deck.<br />
(11S222)<br />
<br />
Play this guy, exert him to put down a forest/dwelling and you’ve essentially played a pump of some sort for most of your Nazgûl, without the cost and hand clog issues of skirmish events. That is great.<br />
<br />
<br />
Úlairë Nertëa, Ninth of the Nine Riders<br />
TW cost: 4 Str: 9 Vit: 2 Site: 3<br />
Lurker. While at a forest site, Úlairë Nertëa is strength +2. While you can spot 6 companions, each Nazgûl is strength +2.<br />
(11S223)<br />
<br />
This guy feeds off of forests, and has a classic ‘spot 6 companions’ bonus. Lurker? Well, in evil men decks it’s a cool theme, but on a single Nazgûl I think it makes little impression. Overall I feel this Nertëa ties with Lemenya (5 of 9) for least effective Nazgûl.<br />
<br />
<br />
Úlairë Toldëa, Eighth of the Nine Riders<br />
TW cost: 6 Str: 12 Vit: 3 Site: 3<br />
Fierce. Each time Úlairë Toldëa wins a skirmish you may play the fellowship’s next site.<br />
(11S225)<br />
<br />
Toldëa will be the heavy hitter in a rare free deck. Playing the next site can work to your advantage, as we shall see, but note that you cannot replace a site ahead of you.<br />
<br />
In the new Black Rider set we find…<br />
<br />
Úlairë Lemenya, Black Enemy<br />
TW cost: 4 Str: 9 Vit: 2 Site: 3<br />
When you play Úlairë Lemenya you may play a [Wraith] mount from your discard pile.<br />
(12U176)<br />
<br />
Ringwraiths are the new kings of deck cycling, and pulling mounts is a very nice ability indeed. More on mounts later.<br />
<br />
Úlairë Nelya, Black Hunter <br />
TW cost: 5 Str: 10 Vit: 3 Site: 2<br />
Fierce. Each time Úlairë Nelya wins a skirmish, you may draw a card.<br />
(12C177)<br />
<br />
Common Nazgûl? What?! So, you can probably draw 2 cards with this Nelya down, but is that necessary? Muster is about, and Nazgûl can cycle like never before. The previous Nelya is far more useful in any deck.<br />
<br />
Úlairë Nertëa, Black Horseman<br />
TW cost: 4 Str: 9 Vit: 2 Site: 3<br />
The twilight cost of each [Wraith] mount is –1. While Úlairë Nertëa is mounted each Nazgûl is strength +1 and has muster.<br />
(12C178)<br />
<br />
This Nertëa (compared to 9 of 9) is a must. Reducing the cost of anything is good news for the expensive Nazgûl, adding muster can also be of great benefit to your deck.<br />
<br />
Úlairë Toldëa, Black Shadow<br />
TW cost: 6 Str: 12 Vit: 3 Site: 3<br />
Fierce. When you play Úlairë Toldëa you may exert him to take a [Wraith] event from your discard pile into hand.<br />
(12U180).<br />
<br />
More cycling- specifically events- given the bonus from sites that in a way negates the need for many skirmish events, this Toldëa allows you to add in those obscure cards, and stock fewer of them.<br />
<br />
Black Rider<br />
TW cost: 5 Str: 8 Vit: 3 Site: 3<br />
Fierce. This minion is strength +1 for each companion you can spot<br />
<br />
The non-unique Nazgûl. This card deserves an article itself. Always Str 9, and possibly Str 17, the Black Rider is a tempting minion, and you could have multiples of him in play at once. However, he does nothing for any Nazgûl strategy, he has no abilities beyond an average strength of 12, and he relies entirely on your opponent’s deck to be effective. If you’re playing Nazgûl, more than any other shadow culture; you must have complete control over your decks functionality. Leave this guy at home. <br />
<br />
Well, that covers the non-rare Ringwraiths now available. They’re essentially old school beat down Nazgûl with added cycling for a faster, more efficient deck. They hit something hard, twice, then return next shadow phase. No corruption, threat, or Enduring weirdness to confuse a new player. Perfect.<br />
<br />
If you go down to the woods today…<br />
<br />
More than ever before, choosing the right sites can and will make or break a deck. Most of the Nazgûl from the Gandalf starter benefit from being at a forest (or dwelling), as do the Hobbits in the Gandalf starter. Even the Forest & Dwelling sites in the box help out your Nazgûl. (These boys at Decipher are getting clever aren’t they?)<br />
<br />
I’ll mention a few sites not in the starter,<br />
<br />
Fangorn Glade (0): Forest: when the fellowship moves here add (1) for each weapon.<br />
<br />
Nazgûl are pricey, this may be a 0 cost site, but the bonus from weapons could really help out, probably better to save this site for later in the game.<br />
<br />
Trollshaw Forest (3): Each time you play an Artifact or Possession on your Companion draw a card.<br />
<br />
High cost, and can help your free peoples, as well as your opponent’s. Then again, if they play bundles of weapons, unload Fangorn glade and reap the reward. Then use Nelya (3 of 9) to swap sites so your opponent doesn’t gain twilight from your possessions. Joy.<br />
<br />
The Angle (0) Forest: Play a Nazgûl (or spot 6 companions and discard 2 cards from hand) to draw a card.<br />
<br />
More cards! More Nazgûl! More Death!<br />
<br />
Ok lets build a deck. Cantëa 4 of 9 is nice and big at a forest or dwelling, and Nelya 3 of 9 gives us that site swapping power. 4 of each will do nicely. Toldëa 8 of 9 gives more site playing goodness, whereas Toldëa, Black Shadow can pull events from our discard pile. 2 of each of this stalwart Nazgûl are essential.<br />
<br />
Lemenya Black Enemy will allow a mount to be played on him from you discard pile, and Nertëa, Black Horseman grants bonuses for being mounted. The mount in question is the new Steed of Mordor. Only +1 strength I know, but draw 2 cards when you win a skirmish? Cool. <br />
<br />
With your hand filling up Riders in Black becomes a really powerful choice (+1 strength for each [Wraith] minion in your hand). Remember as a skirmish event Toldëa, Black Shadow can pull this card back from your discard pile.<br />
<br />
Time for some other stuff. With forests in abundance, it’d foolish not to add Lost in the Woods, which sits on a companion, giving a Nazgûl skirmishing them +1 strength for each forest you can spot. Mmm. <br />
If we’re planning to win skirmishes, and we are, swords help. Nazgûl Blade gives +1 Str, and another +1 if at a forest (or battle ground)<br />
Just won a fierce skirmish? Use Hatred Stirred to shuffle a discarded [Wraith] card back into your draw deck. <br />
(Note: when using this card, remember we have ways of grabbing mounts, events and even minions, so choose something you couldn’t otherwise cycle, in particular conditions, or Nazgûl Blade.)<br />
Finally, we’ve Moving this way and Minas Morgul Answer. The former will cycle Nazgûl out of your hand in case you get clogged with three of the same minion, and the latter gives a little condition removal to scupper your opponent’s plans.<br />
<br />
32-card shadow side:<br />
Úlairë Cantëa, Fourth of the Nine Riders x4<br />
Úlairë Lemenya, Black Enemy x2<br />
Úlairë Nelya, Third of the Nine Riders x4<br />
Úlairë Nertëa, Black Horseman x2<br />
Úlairë Toldëa, Eighth of the Nine Riders x2<br />
Úlairë Toldëa, Black Shadow x2<br />
Steed of Mordor x3<br />
Nazgûl Blade x3<br />
Lost in the Woods x2<br />
Hatred Stirred x2<br />
Moving this way x2<br />
Minas Morgul Answer x2<br />
Riders in Black x2<br />
<br />
Your choice sites will also depend on your Free Peoples side, suffice to say the more forests & dwellings the better. Use the Nazgûl friendly sites from the Gandalf starter and go from there.<br />
<br />
It’s almost too easy isn’t it? Once you start adding big rare minions and other cards you’ll find your own tactics and playing style. Just remember when picking up a new culture to start of with a simple deck, learn the basis of the culture, and then go for the ultimate corruption deck or super wounding deck.<br />
<br />
Should this article prove to popular and well rated, I shall write an intermediate article with notes on various (post rotation) Nazgûl deck types.<br />
<br />
Enjoy, and make sure other people enjoy playing.<br />
‘Nuff said.<br />
<br />
El Spanko.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
